\begin{abstract}

\noindent A continuous-energy Monte Carlo neutronics and depletion model of the Advanced Burner Reactor (ABR-1000) sodium-cooled fast reactor (SFR) was developed using OpenMC. The model represents an equilibrium transuranic (TRU)-recycled metal fuel core based on the ANL-AFCI-202 reference design \cite{ANL2007} and the OECD/NEA benchmark specifications \cite{NEA2016}. A homogenized cylindrical approximation was employed to represent the 379-assembly hexagonal core, with five-zone axial and two-zone radial fuel composition stratification consistent with benchmark definitions. The depletable fuel inventory is discretized into ten distinct material regions (five axial, two radial), and a predictor-corrector (CECM) integration scheme is used over a 12-step geometric timestep schedule spanning 328.5 effective full-power days (EFPD). \\

\noindent The final model achieves a beginning-of-cycle (BOC) effective multiplication factor of $k_{\mathrm{eff}} \approx$ 1.04916, in reasonable agreement with the benchmark average of $1.0355 \pm 0.0078$ \cite{NEA2016}. Depletion analysis reproduces key fuel cycle performance metrics, including a burnup reactivity swing of approximately -2415~pcm (benchmark: $2210 \pm 422$~pcm) and a TRU consumption rate of approximately 94.8~kg/year (ANL reference: 81.6~kg/year). \\

\noindent Remaining discrepancies relative to deterministic benchmark participants are attributed primarily to geometric simplifications inherent in the cylindrical homogenization and the use of natural molybdenum as a pseudo-fission product surrogate in lieu of an explicit fission product chain. The model provides a physically consistent framework for further studies of fast reactor fuel cycle performance and equilibrium core behavior.

\end{abstract}

