\section{Introduction}

\noindent Sodium-cooled fast reactors (SFRs) occupy a central role in advanced nuclear fuel cycle strategies owing to their ability to efficiently fission transuranic (TRU) isotopes recovered from light water reactor (LWR) spent nuclear fuel. By operating on a hard neutron spectrum, SFRs achieve TRU conversion ratios substantially below unity, enabling sustained actinide burning that reduces the long-term radiotoxicity and heat load of nuclear waste \cite{ANL2007}. The Advanced Burner Reactor (ABR-1000), developed by Argonne National Laboratory (ANL) under the Global Nuclear Energy Partnership (GNEP) program, is a 1000~MWt pool-type SFR designed for a closed fuel cycle with recycled metallic U-TRU-Zr fuel and a target TRU conversion ratio of approximately 0.7 \cite{ANL2007}.\\

\noindent Accurate neutronics modeling of SFR cores presents several challenges that distinguish them from thermal-spectrum systems. The fast spectrum demands high-fidelity cross-section data across the unresolved resonance region, where probability table sampling is essential. The absence of significant thermalization also reduces the sensitivity of $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ to geometric approximations, though the spatial distribution of fissile material and the treatment of leakage remain important. In depletion calculations, the complex multi-isotope TRU composition evolves rapidly under high fast fluences, requiring consistent tracking of minor actinides and accurate transmutation chains. \\

\noindent Monte Carlo methods provide a rigorous framework for capturing these effects without reliance on group-collapsing approximations, diffusion theory, or spatial homogenization of individual pins. The OpenMC code \cite{Romano2015} offers continuous-energy transport, a modern depletion interface via the openmc.deplete module, and direct compatibility with ENDF/B-VIII.0 cross-section libraries, making it well-suited to this class of problems. \\

\noindent In this work, OpenMC is used to develop a continuous-energy model of the ABR-1000 equilibrium TRU-recycled metal core. Eigenvalue and full-cycle depletion calculations are performed to evaluate reactivity, power distribution, and fuel cycle performance. The model is measured against published ANL and OECD/NEA results \cite{ANL2007,NEA2016,Kim2012,Niloy2023}, with particular attention to sources of bias arising from the cylindrical geometry approximation and the homogenized material treatment adopted in this work. \\

\section{Core Design Description}

\subsection{Reference Core Layout}

\noindent The ABR-1000 reference core is a compact, pool-type SFR of 1000~MWt rated thermal power, designed for a one-year irradiation cycle (328.5 EFPD at 90\% capacity factor) with a four-batch fuel management scheme \cite{ANL2007}. The hexagonal core lattice employs an assembly pitch of 16.142~cm with a flat-to-flat duct dimension of 15.710~cm and an inter-assembly gap of 0.432~cm. The full core contains 379 assemblies: 180 driver fuel assemblies divided into 78 inner-core and 102 outer-core positions, 114 radial reflector assemblies, 66 radial shield assemblies, and 19 control assemblies (15 primary and 4 secondary) \cite{ANL2007,NEA2016}. Figure~1 illustrates the reference radial core layout.\\

