\subsection{Control Assemblies}

\noindent The primary control system uses boron carbide absorber assemblies with two B-10 enrichment levels: natural boron (19.9 at\% $^{10}$B) for the fourth-row assemblies and 60\% enriched boron for the seventh-row assemblies. Secondary control assemblies use natural boron. In this model, control assemblies are accounted for by volume-fraction blending of the absorber material into the fuel zone, assuming rods fully withdrawn (BOEC condition), consistent with benchmark practice \cite{NEA2016}. \\

\section{Neutronics Modeling and Methodology}

\subsection{Geometry Approximation}

\noindent The hexagonal 379-assembly core is represented using a homogenized cylindrical approximation, wherein each hexagonal ring of assemblies is collapsed into a concentric annular region of equivalent cross-sectional area. The effective radius of an annulus enclosing $n$ assemblies is given by:

\begin{equation}
R_{\mathrm{eff}}(n) = \sqrt{\frac{n \cdot A_{\mathrm{hex}}}{\pi}},
\quad A_{\mathrm{hex}} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} p^2
\end{equation}

\noindent where $p = 16.142$~cm is the assembly pitch and $A_{\mathrm{hex}}$ is the area of a regular hexagon. This yields the following radial boundaries: \\

\begin{align}
R_{\mathrm{inner}}  &= R_{\mathrm{eff}}(85)  = \text{78.13708}~\mathrm{cm} \\
R_{\mathrm{outer}}  &= R_{\mathrm{eff}}(199) = \text{119.55679}~\mathrm{cm} \\
R_{\mathrm{refl}}   &= R_{\mathrm{eff}}(313) = \text{149.94082}~\mathrm{cm} \\
R_{\mathrm{shield}} &= R_{\mathrm{eff}}(379) = \text{164.99369}~\mathrm{cm}
\end{align}

\noindent The model employs vacuum boundary conditions on all outer surfaces (radial and axial), consistent with the benchmark specification \cite{NEA2016}. Schematics of the homogenized cylindrical model are shown in Figures~2 and 3. \\

