\subsection{Material Homogenization}

\noindent Within each radial and axial zone, materials are homogenized at the assembly level. The active-core material in each zone is a volume-fraction-weighted mixture of fuel (39.0\%), sodium coolant (35.34\%), and HT9 structural material (25.66\%) \cite{NEA2016}. Number densities for each constituent are taken directly from the benchmark specification (Tables~2.20--2.23 of Ref.~\cite{NEA2016}) and scaled by the corresponding volume fraction. The control assembly contribution is incorporated by blending the empty-duct (withdrawn rod) material into the active zone at the appropriate assembly fraction: $f_{\mathrm{ci}} = 7/85$ for the inner zone and $f_{\mathrm{co}} = 12/114$ for the outer zone. \\

\noindent Non-fuel axial regions (lower structure, lower reflector, displaced bond sodium, gas plenum, and upper structure) are represented as binary sodium--HT9 mixtures at volume fractions consistent with Tables~2.20 of Ref.~\cite{NEA2016}. The radial reflector is a dense HT9/sodium mixture (84.5\% HT9), and the radial shield contains boron carbide with natural isotopic enrichment in addition to HT9 and sodium \cite{NEA2016}. \\

\subsection{Nuclear Data}

\noindent Continuous-energy cross sections from the ENDF/B-VIII.0 nuclear data library are used throughout. Temperature-dependent cross sections are applied using OpenMC's built-in interpolation scheme. Material temperatures are set to $T_{\mathrm{fuel}} = 807.15$~K (average fuel temperature corresponding to 534.0$^\circ$C) and $T_{\mathrm{struct}} = T_{\mathrm{cool}} = 705.65$~K (coolant and structural average corresponding to 432.5$^\circ$C), consistent with the nominal operating condition specified in the benchmark \cite{NEA2016}. No S($\alpha$,$\beta$) thermal scattering treatment is applied, as is appropriate for liquid sodium and metallic structural materials at these temperatures. \\

\subsection{Depletion Methodology}

\noindent Depletion is performed using the openmc.deplete.CoupledOperator interface with the ENDF/B-VIII.0 SFR transmutation chain (chain\_endfb80\_sfr.xml). The predictor--corrector mid-point (CECM) integration scheme is employed, which requires two transport solves per timestep and achieves second-order accuracy in the burnup evolution \cite{Romano2015}. This method is appropriate for the moderate burnup rates characteristic of the ABR cycle ($\approx$73.2~kW/kg HM). \\

\noindent The timestep schedule consists of 12 geometric steps spanning the full 328.5~EFPD cycle, computed via numpy.geomspace between 0.5~d and 328.5~d. Early timesteps (on the order of days) resolve the short-lived fission product equilibration transients, including the $^{135}$Xe equilibrium ($\sim$40~h) and the $^{149}$Sm equilibrium ($\sim$4~d). Later timesteps (up to $\sim$138~d) track the slow actinide evolution. The timestep schedule is presented in Table~3. \\

