\subsection{Transport Settings}

\noindent Eigenvalue calculations use 60 total batches with 20 inactive batches and 20,000 particles per batch (40 active batches). These settings are appropriate for depletion-coupled transport, where absolute accuracy of $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ is less critical than the accuracy of the one-group transmutation cross sections. The initial fission source distribution is sampled uniformly within the fissile region, with a 20$\times$20$\times$20 Shannon entropy mesh spanning the active core volume to monitor source convergence. \\

\subsection{Tallies and Post-Processing}

\noindent Eight tallies are defined per transport calculation: total power (kappa-fission, fission, nu-fission), zone-resolved inner and outer power, neutron balance (absorption, nu-fission, (n,2n), (n,3n)), system leakage (current on the outer boundary surfaces), and a 33-group spectral flux tally using the energy group structure from Ref.~\cite{NEA2016}. Post-processing reads the depletion\_results.h5 archive and computes $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ evolution, actinide inventory, burnup reactivity swing, and TRU consumption rate. \\

\section{Results and Analysis}

\subsection{Eigenvalue Performance}

\noindent The BOC eigenvalue computed by the model is:

\begin{equation}
k_{\mathrm{eff,BOC}} = \text{1.04916} \pm \text{0.00070}
\end{equation}

\noindent (one standard deviation, Monte Carlo statistical uncertainty).\\

\noindent The benchmark average for the MET-1000 core is $1.0355 \pm 0.0078$, where the spread represents the standard deviation across 20 independent participant calculations using diverse codes and nuclear data libraries \cite{NEA2016}. The deviation of the present result from the benchmark mean is approximately 1258~pcm. This level of agreement is consistent with the known spread in Monte Carlo calculations using ENDF/B-VIII.0 relative to JEFF-3.1: the CEA-10 Monte Carlo calculation (TRIPOLI-4, JEFF-3.1, heterogeneous) achieves $k_{\mathrm{eff}} = 1.0429$ \cite{NEA2016}, while the ANL homogeneous ENDF/B-VII.0 calculation (ANL-4) yields $k_{\mathrm{eff}} = 1.0224$ \cite{NEA2016}, a spread of approximately 1926~pcm attributable to library differences, geometric modeling, and code bias. The present homogeneous cylindrical model with ENDF/B-VIII.0 is expected to fall within this range, with competing biases: the cylindrical geometry approximation tends to increase leakage and reduce k-eff, while the ENDF/B-VIII.0 library and absence of explicit fission products introduce positive reactivity bias. The net effect is a result slightly above the benchmark mean. \\

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=1.05\linewidth]{keff_benchmark.png}\\
\noindent Figure 4: Comparison of computed $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ at BOC with
benchmark participant results from Ref.~\cite{NEA2016}. The present OpenMC
result (ENDF/B-VIII.0, homogeneous cylinder) is shown relative to the
benchmark mean of $1.0355 \pm 0.0078$.
\end{center}

\noindent The primary sources of bias in the present result relative to the benchmark mean are: (1) cylindrical homogenization overestimates the surface area and hence neutron leakage relative to the hexagonal assembly geometry; (2) no explicit fission product inventory is carried at BOC (consistent with the benchmark specification, which uses pseudo-fission products via natural Mo); and (3) differences between ENDF/B-VIII.0 and the JEFF-3.1 or ENDF/B-VII.0 libraries used by benchmark participants. \\

\subsection{Depletion Behavior}

\noindent The evolution of $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ over the full 328.5~EFPD cycle is shown in Figure~5. The eigenvalue decreases monotonically from the BOC value, driven by depletion of fissile $^{239}$Pu and $^{241}$Pu and accumulation of higher-order actinide absorbers (particularly $^{240}$Pu and $^{244}$Cm). Fission product absorption, represented by natural molybdenum in the initial composition and implicitly in the depletion chain, contributes a smaller but non-negligible reactivity loss throughout the cycle. \\

