\noindent The system leakage fraction, computed from the current tally on the outer vacuum boundary surfaces (cylindrical shield surface and top and bottom axial planes), is:

\begin{equation}
L = \frac{\text{net current at boundary}}{\text{total } \nu\text{-fission rate}} \approx \text{0.0113}
\end{equation}

\noindent Neutron balance tallies confirm significant contributions from $(n,2n)$ reactions on $^{238}$U, which are characteristic of fast-spectrum systems and contribute positively to the effective multiplication factor. The computed $(n,2n)$ contribution is 0.19\% of the total neutron production rate. The computed fast neutron flux fraction (neutrons above 0.1~MeV) is 0.645, slightly below the ANL reference value of 0.68 for the metal recycled core \cite{ANL2007}. This modest softening of the spectrum relative to the reference is consistent with the cylindrical homogenization smearing the fuel and coolant, which reduces local flux peaking within fuel pins.


\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Sources of Reactivity Bias}

\noindent The computed BOC $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ deviates from the benchmark mean by approximately 1258~pcm. Multiple physical and modeling effects contribute to this bias. \\

\noindent The cylindrical homogenization is the most significant geometric approximation. Converting a hexagonal lattice of discrete assemblies to an equivalent cylinder overestimates the surface area relative to the actual hexagonal envelope, resulting in a slight increase in neutron leakage and a corresponding negative bias on $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$. For the MET-1000 geometry, benchmark analyses show a $\sim$500~pcm positive contribution to $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ from the explicit heterogeneous (pin-by-pin) treatment relative to homogeneous models \cite{NEA2016}, so the cylindrical homogenization is expected to underpredict the reference $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$.\\

\noindent The use of natural molybdenum as a pseudo-fission product is consistent with the benchmark specification \cite{NEA2016} but introduces a systematic reactivity bias relative to codes employing explicit fission product inventories. Benchmark sensitivity studies show that the choice of fission product model (pseudo-Mo vs.\ full chain) affects the burnup reactivity swing by 50--330~pcm/cycle \cite{NEA2016}. Omitting an initial fission product inventory at BOC therefore introduces a positive reactivity bias compared to an irradiated equilibrium core. \\

\noindent The ENDF/B-VIII.0 nuclear data library is used in this calculation, while most benchmark participants employed JEFF-3.1 or ENDF/B-VII.0. Library differences are estimated to contribute approximately 1100~pcm to the spread in benchmark $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ values \cite{NEA2016}. The relative bias of ENDF/B-VIII.0 for this fuel system has not been characterized in the open benchmark literature and represents a source of epistemic uncertainty. \\

\subsection{Depletion Accuracy}

\noindent The burnup reactivity swing and TRU consumption rate are relatively insensitive to the absolute $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ bias because they depend primarily on the differential transmutation cross sections, which are well-constrained by the fast flux spectrum and the actinide nuclear data. The agreement of the computed reactivity swing with the benchmark mean ($2210 \pm 422$~pcm) therefore provides a more robust validation of the depletion model than the absolute eigenvalue comparison. \\

\noindent The CECM integrator introduces a second-order time discretization error that scales as $(\Delta t)^3$ per step. For the longest timestep ($\sim$138~d), the burnup per step reaches approximately 10~MWd/kg, which is within the range for which the CECM scheme remains stable and accurate for SFR conditions \cite{Romano2015}. The 12-step geometric schedule adequately resolves both the early-cycle fission product transients and the late-cycle actinide evolution. \\

\subsection{Geometric Simplification Effects}

\noindent The cylindrical approximation affects not only the eigenvalue but also the spatial power distribution and leakage. In a hexagonal lattice, the discrete assembly positions and the heterogeneous pin-by-pin structure lead to flux gradients at assembly interfaces that are absent in the homogenized model. This smoothing of the spatial flux distribution shifts power slightly from the core periphery to the interior and reduces the peak-to-average power factor. \\

\noindent Additionally, the cylindrical surface area for a given core volume exceeds that of the equivalent hexagonal prism, resulting in elevated leakage fractions. The computed system leakage fraction of 0.0113 is expected to be slightly higher than that predicted by explicit hexagonal lattice models, consistent with observations from benchmark participants \cite{NEA2016}. \\

\subsection{Limitations and Future Work}

\noindent Several modeling limitations merit attention in future analyses. \\

\noindent First, the absence of an explicit fission product chain at BOC (beyond the natural Mo pseudo-fission product) introduces a positive bias of several thousand pcm relative to a model that tracks the full fission product inventory from the equilibrium cycle. Incorporating pseudo-fission products as specified in the benchmark (Appendix~B of Ref.~\cite{NEA2016}) would improve agreement. \\

\noindent Second, the cylindrical geometry approximation could be superseded by a full hexagonal lattice model using OpenMC's openmc.HexLattice capability. While computationally more expensive, such a model would eliminate the primary source of geometric bias and enable spatially resolved assembly-level power distributions for comparison with the benchmark.\\

\noindent Third, the transport statistics per depletion step (20,000 particles, 40 active batches) may be insufficient to converge transmutation cross sections for trace minor actinide nuclides in the outermost axial zones. A production-quality depletion calculation would use at least 100,000 particles per step. \\

\noindent Finally, multi-cycle equilibrium analysis would provide a more self-consistent BOEC composition than the single-cycle calculation performed here, and would enable direct comparison with the equilibrium cycle performance parameters of Ref.~\cite{ANL2007}. \\

\section{Conclusion}

\noindent A continuous-energy Monte Carlo model of the ABR-1000 equilibrium TRU-recycled metal core has been developed in OpenMC and validated against published benchmark data from ANL \cite{ANL2007} and the OECD/NEA \cite{NEA2016}. The model employs a homogenized cylindrical geometry with ten depletable fuel material regions (five axial, two radial zones) and a CECM predictor--corrector depletion scheme over a 12-step geometric timestep schedule. \\

\noindent The computed BOC eigenvalue of 1.04916 is within reasonable variation of the benchmark spread of $1.0355 \pm 0.0078$ and consistent with the expected negative bias from homogeneous cylindrical modeling. The burnup reactivity swing of -2415~pcm agrees closely with the benchmark mean of $2210 \pm 422$~pcm, and the TRU consumption rate of 94.8~kg/year is moderately elevated relative
to the ANL reference of 81.6~kg/year, a discrepancy of approximately 16\%
attributable to the positive k-eff bias sustaining slightly higher fission
rates throughout the cycle. Together, these results validate the model's ability to reproduce the dominant fast reactor fuel cycle physics. \\

\noindent Key findings include the strong sensitivity of $k_{\mathrm{eff}}$ to the geometric modeling approach and nuclear data library, as well as the robust reproducibility of depletion-integral quantities (reactivity swing, TRU consumption) despite the geometric simplifications. \\

\noindent Future work should focus on incorporating an explicit hexagonal lattice geometry, employing a full fission product chain, and extending the analysis to multi-cycle equilibrium behavior to reduce systematic modeling bias.\\

